## DELETE /api/products/{id}  (admin only)

Scenario 15. CAT-009: a product that has been part of at least one placed
order can never be permanently deleted, only deactivated. A product that
has never been ordered may be removed outright.

Request — a product with no order history:
```json
DELETE /api/products/10000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000099
Authorization: Bearer <jwt for admin>
```

Response — 204 No Content.

Request — a product that has been ordered (e.g. prod-0001, once Phase 5's
order exists referencing it):
```json
DELETE /api/products/10000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000001
Authorization: Bearer <jwt for admin>
```

Response — 409 Conflict:
```json
{
  "error": {
    "code": "PRODUCT_HAS_ORDER_HISTORY",
    "message": "This product has been part of at least one order and can only be deactivated, not deleted."
  }
}
```

This check depends on order-service data that doesn't exist until Phase
5 — catalog-service has to ask order-service (or a materialized flag kept
in sync some other way) whether the product ID appears in any order_items
row. That's a real cross-service question this phase's implementation has
to answer, not something to gloss over; flagging it here rather than
guessing at the mechanism, since Archive/Development/Database doesn't
specify one (CAT-009 is a business rule, not a wire-level design).

---

## Regression check against Phase 3

- GET /api/products and GET /api/products/{id} must reflect every mutation
  above immediately — a deactivated or edited product's browse-facing
  fields (name, category, unitPrice, inStock) must never show stale data.
